<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="138" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1044,1899]" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,312,1044,1070]" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Description:—</emphasis>
Frustules in girdle view wedge-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[784,874,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Valves slightly heteropolar, narrowly clavate to linear-lanceolate with narrowly rounded and not protracted headpole and footpole (
<figureCitation box="[1074,1176,1080,1106]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1952,1974]" captionTargetBox="[201,1404,533,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-178@2.[151,1436,502,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 2–19. LM micrographs. 2–7. Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P.Almeida sp. nov. 8–15. Planothidium lanceolatum. 16–19. Planothidium frequentissimum. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820927" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820927/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Figs 2–7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1188,1348,1080,1107]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">20, 23, 25, 26</figureCitation>
). Largest width near the mid-valve. Valve dimensions (n = 12): length 5.0–8.0 µm, width 2.2–3.0 µm. Axial area rather wide, lanceolate, widening slightly towards the central area (
<figureCitation box="[755,975,1152,1179]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Figs 20, 23, 25, 26</figureCitation>
). Raphe is straight with slightly expanded drop-like proximal endings (
<figureCitation box="[457,588,1188,1214]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Figs 21–23</figureCitation>
). Internally, proximal raphe endings are short, unilaterally deflected as small hooks (
<figureCitation box="[218,351,1224,1250]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Figs 20, 22</figureCitation>
). Distal external raphe endings are very short, straight, slightly expanded into drop-like pores and not extended into the valve mantle (
<figureCitation box="[538,711,1260,1287]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Figs 23, 25, 26</figureCitation>
). At LM view, striae are difficult to resolve due to the small valve size (
<figureCitation box="[193,293,1296,1322]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1952,1974]" captionTargetBox="[201,1404,533,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-178@2.[151,1436,502,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 2–19. LM micrographs. 2–7. Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P.Almeida sp. nov. 8–15. Planothidium lanceolatum. 16–19. Planothidium frequentissimum. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820927" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820927/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Figs 2–7</figureCitation>
). Transapical uniseriate striae weakly radiate, becoming almost parallel mid-valve, 18–25 striae in 10 μm. Each stria is composed of a single transversely elongated areola both externally and internally (
<figureCitation box="[1200,1414,1332,1359]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Figs 20–23, 25, 26</figureCitation>
). A row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction) is located on the valve mantle in girdle view (
<figureCitation box="[1325,1409,1368,1394]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–26" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1508,1530]" captionTargetBox="[192,1402,193,1472]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,187,1486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 20–26. SEM micrographs of Gomphosphenia minima C. Delgado, S. Blanco, L. González-Paz &amp; S.F.P. Almeida sp. nov. 20. Internal valve view showing the raphe ending and the transapical uniseriate striae. 21. External view of the central area showing the raphe ending slightly expanded into drop-like pores. 22. Internal view of the central area showing the raphe ending curved to one side. 23. External view of the valve showing the striae composed of a single areola. 24. Girdle view of the entire frustule showing the mantle striae composed by row of individual pores (elongated in the pervalvar direction). 25. External valve showing the narrowly rounded headpole. 26. External valve showing the narrowly rounded footpole. Scale bar = 1 μm (Figs 20–26)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6820929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6820929/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="138">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
